Module 6: Data Visualizations in R

Introduction

In this tutorial, we learn how to visualize the data using package “ggplot2”. Although R has several functions for creating visualizations, package “ggplot2” is widely used for creating aesthetic visualizations in R. “ggplot2” implements the grammar of graphics, a coherent system for describing and building graphs.

We first need to load the library:

library(ggplot2)

Note: If we need to be explicit about where a function (or dataset) comes from, we’ll use the special form package::function(). For example, ggplot2::ggplot() tells us explicitly that we’re using the ggplot() function from the “ggplot2” package.

In this module, we use salary data set we have used in the previous modules:

salary <- read.csv("salary_data.csv", strip.white = T, na.strings = "?")

How ggplot Works

  • Layering is a key concept in plotting with the ggplot2 package. That is, ggplot2 attempts to move users away from thinking about point and click interfaces that produce one single graphic. Instead, the hope is to give users the freedom to think about the graphics they would like to create in a highly customizable framework.
  • ggplot2 has the desirable property of allowing users to use more modular pieces of code to create beautiful plots exactly to the user’s specification [1]
  • You can read up on the Grammer of ggplot here

Creating a ggplot

In the very first step, we create a bar plot for variable education in dataset salary:

ggplot(data = salary) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education))

The plot shows the number of observations with respect to variable education.

With “ggplot2”, we initiate a plot with the function ggplot(), which creates a coordinate system that we can add layers to. The first argument of ggplot() is the dataset to use in the plot. So ggplot(data = salary) creates an empty plot based on data salary. It is empty because we have not specified

  1. what type of plot we want to create and
  2. which variable(s) should be used in the plot.

We complete our plot by adding one or more layers to ggplot(). The function geom_bar() adds a layer of bars to our plot, which creates a barplot. “ggplot2” comes with many geom functions that each add a different type of layer to a plot. We’ll learn a some of the most important layers of ggplot().

  • Each geom function in “ggplot2” takes a mapping argument.
    • This defines how variables in our dataset are mapped to visual properties. The mapping argument is always paired with aes(),
    • The x and y arguments of aes() specify which variables to map to the x and y axes (In many types of plots, including the barplot in our example, we could have only an x axis and no y axis).
    • “ggplot2” looks for the mapped variables in the data argument, in this case, salary.

Here is the basic structure of ggplot():

ggplot(data = <DATA>) +
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>)

We can also save the ggplot object for later use:

p1 <- ggplot(data = salary)

And then we can just add the mapping to the ggplot object to create the plot:

p1 + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education))

This gets us a bar chart with no colors. It is still kind of a mess, but we have a plot. We can flip the coordinates of the plot to make it look better:

p1 + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education)) + coord_flip()

This way, we can see the categories of education better.

We can also add another variable (“sex”) as the color of the plot:

p1 + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, fill = sex)) + coord_flip()

Or, we could add a title to our plot:

p1 + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, fill = sex)) + coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("Count of education categories by gender")

Now, let’s create different types of plots:

Histogram: 

p1 + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = age)) 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Now, let’s change the binwidth of the histogram:

p1 + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = age), binwidth = 1)

or again create the plot by gender:

p1 + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = age, fill = sex), binwidth = 1)

Scatterplot: 

p1 + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))

Separated by gender:

p1 + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, colour = sex))

We can also use contrast instead of color. This is a good optin for differentiating the points based on a numeric variable:

# Left
p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, alpha = education.num))

Instead of color, we could change the size of the data points in the scatterplot based on a variable:

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, size = education.num))

#> Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Or the shape:

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, shape = sex))

We can also use the same variable for both shape and color:

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, shape = sex, colour = sex))

Or shape and contrast:

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, alpha = education.num, shape = sex))

Another common type of plot is

Boxplot: 

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = sex, y = hours.per.week))

We can remove the outliers from the boxplot by using argument outlier.shape:

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = sex, y = hours.per.week), outlier.shape=NA)

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = workclass, y = hours.per.week), outlier.shape=NA)

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = education, y = hours.per.week), outlier.shape=NA) +
  coord_flip()

We can use variable sex to color the visualization:

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = education, y = hours.per.week,
               fill = sex), outlier.shape=NA) +
  coord_flip()

Now we use salary.class to color the visualization:

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = education, y = hours.per.week,
               fill = salary.class), outlier.shape=NA) +
  coord_flip()

We can modify the title of the coordinates:

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = education, y = hours.per.week,
               fill = salary.class), outlier.shape=NA) +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_discrete(name ="Hours Worked per Week",
                    limits=seq(0,80,5)) +
  scale_x_discrete(name ="Education Level")

For a comprehensive list of plots we can create using ggplot2, please refer to: https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ggplot2-cheatsheet.pdf

Facets

One way to add additional variables is with aesthetics. Another way, particularly useful for categorical variables, is to split our plot into facets, subplots that each display one subset of the data.

To facet our plot by a single variable, use facet_wrap(). The first argument of facet_wrap() should be a formula, which we create with ~ followed by a variable name (here “formula” is the name of a data structure in R, not a synonym for “equation”). The variable that we pass to facet_wrap() should be discrete.

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain)) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex, nrow = 2)

To facet our plot on the combination of two variables, add facet_grid() to ourr plot call. The first argument of facet_grid() is also a formula. This time the formula should contain two variable names separated by a ~.

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))  +
  facet_grid(workclass ~ sex)

If we prefer to not facet in the rows or columns dimension, use a . instead of a variable name, e.g. + facet_grid(. ~ sex).

Geometric objects

A geom is the geometrical object that a plot uses to represent data. People often describe plots by the type of geom that the plot uses. For example, bar charts use bar geoms, line charts use line geoms, boxplots use boxplot geoms, and so on. Scatterplots break the trend; they use the point geom. As we see above, we can use different geoms to plot the same data. The plot on the left uses the point geom, and the plot on the right uses the smooth geom, a smooth line fitted to the data.

To change the geom in our plot, change the geom function that we add to ggplot(). For instance, to make the plots above, we can use this code:

# left
p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))

# right
p1 +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Every geom function in “ggplot2” takes a mapping argument. However, not every aesthetic works with every geom. We could set the shape of a point, but we couldn’t set the “shape” of a line. On the other hand, we could set the linetype of a line. geom_smooth() will draw a different line, with a different linetype, for each unique value of the variable that we map to linetype.

p1 +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, linetype = sex))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Here geom_smooth() separates the observations into two lines based on their sex value.

“ggplot2” provides over 30 geoms, and extension packages provide even more (see https://www.ggplot2-exts.org for a sampling). The best way to get a comprehensive overview is the “ggplot2” cheatsheet, which we can find at http://rstudio.com/cheatsheets. To learn more about any single geom, use help: ?geom_smooth.

Many geoms, like geom_smooth(), use a single geometric object to display multiple rows of data. For these geoms, we can set the group aesthetic to a categorical variable to draw multiple objects.

  • “ggplot2” will draw a separate object for each unique value of the grouping variable.
  • In practice, “ggplot2” will automatically group the data for these geoms whenever we map an aesthetic to a discrete variable (as in the linetype example).
  • It is convenient to rely on this feature because the group aesthetic by itself does not add a legend or distinguishing features to the geoms.
p1 +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

p1 +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, group = sex))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

p1 +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain, color = sex),
    show.legend = FALSE
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

To display multiple geoms in the same plot, add multiple geom functions to ggplot():

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

This, however, introduces some duplication in our code. Imagine if we wanted to change the y-axis to display another variable. We’d need to change the variable in two places, and we might forget to update one.

  • We can avoid this type of repetition by passing a set of mappings to ggplot().
    • “ggplot2” will treat these mappings as global mappings that apply to each geom in the graph. In other words, this code will produce the same plot as the previous code:
ggplot(data = salary, mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

If we place mappings in a geom function, “ggplot2” will treat them as local mappings for the layer. It will use these mappings to extend or overwrite the global mappings for that layer only. This makes it possible to display different aesthetics in different layers.

ggplot(data = salary, mapping = aes(x = age, y = capital.gain)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = sex)) +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Now, let’s create a scatterplot but only for females in our data. To do so, we use tidyverse to filter the data and then we use ggplot2 to visualize the results:

salary %>%

salary %>%

salary %>%

salary %>%

Statistical Transformations

Consider a basic bar chart, as drawn with geom_bar():

p1 +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education)) +
  coord_flip()

On the x-axis (which we flipped in the visualization above), the chart displays education, a variable from salary. On the y-axis, it displays count, but count is not a variable in salary! Where does count come from? Many graphs, like scatterplots, plot the raw values of our dataset. Other graphs, like bar charts, calculate new values to plot:

  • bar charts, histograms, and frequency polygons bin our data and then plot bin counts, the number of points that fall in each bin.

  • smoothers fit a model to our data and then plot predictions from the model.

  • boxplots compute a robust summary of the distribution and then display a specially formatted box.

The algorithm used to calculate new values for a graph is called a stat, short for statistical transformation. We can learn which stat a geom uses by inspecting the default value for the stat argument. For example, ?geom_bar shows that the default value for stat is “count”, which means that geom_bar() uses stat_count(). stat_count() is documented on the same page as geom_bar(), and if we scroll down we can find a section called “Computed variables”. That describes how it computes two new variables: count and prop.

We can generally use geoms and stats interchangeably. For example, we can recreate the previous plot using stat_count() instead of geom_bar():

p1 +
  stat_count(mapping = aes(x = education)) +
  coord_flip()

This works because every geom has a default stat; and every stat has a default geom. This means that we can typically use geoms without worrying about the underlying statistical transformation. But we could change the stats if wanted to. For instance, we use proportions instead of count:

p1 +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, y = ..prop.., group = 1)) +
  coord_flip()

The plot shows that for instance over 30% of observations have HS-grad as the value of education.

We might want to draw greater attention to the statistical transformation in our code. For example, we can use stat_summary(), which summarises the y values for each unique x value, to draw attention to the summary that we’re computing:

p1 +
  stat_summary(
    mapping = aes(x = education, y = hours.per.week),
    fun.ymin = min,
    fun.ymax = max,
    fun.y = median
  ) +
  coord_flip()

“ggplot2” provides over 20 stats. Each stat is a function, so we can get help in the usual way, e.g. ?stat_bin. To see a complete list of stats, we can try the “ggplot2” cheatsheet

Position Adjustments

1- Setting position to identity creates the following plot:

p1 +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, fill = salary.class), position = "identity")

2- position = "fill" works like stacking, but makes each set of stacked bars the same height. This makes it easier to compare proportions across groups.

p1 +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, fill = salary.class), position = "fill")

3- position = "dodge" places overlapping objects directly beside one another. This makes it easier to compare individual values.

p1 +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = education, fill = salary.class), position = "dodge")

There’s one other type of adjustment that’s not useful for bar charts, but it can be very useful for scatterplots. Let’s take a look at the following scatterplot:

p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = hours.per.week))

The values of age and hours.per.week are rounded so the points appear on a grid and many points overlap each other. This problem is known as overplotting. We can avoid this gridding by setting the position adjustment to “jitter”.

  • position = "jitter" adds a small amount of random noise to each point.
  • This spreads the points out because no two points are likely to receive the same amount of random noise.
p1 +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = age, y = hours.per.week), position = "jitter")

Adding randomness seems like a strange way to improve our plot, but while it makes our graph less accurate at small scales, it makes it more revealing at large scales. Because this is such a useful operation, “ggplot2” comes with a shorthand for geom_point(position = "jitter"): geom_jitter().

To learn more about a position adjustment, look up the help page associated with each adjustment: ?position_dodge, ?position_fill, ?position_identity, ?position_jitter, and ?position_stack.

Coordinate systems

We have already discussed why in certain cases we need to flip the coordinates:

1- coord_flip() switches the x and y axes. This is useful (for example), if we want horizontal boxplots. It’s also useful for long labels: it’s hard to get them to fit without overlapping on the x-axis.

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = education, y = capital.gain), outlier.shape=NA) +
  scale_y_discrete(name ="Capital Gain",
                    limits=seq(0,20000,1000))

p1 +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = education, y = capital.gain), outlier.shape=NA) +
  scale_y_discrete(name ="Capital Gain",
                    limits=seq(0,20000,1000)) +
  coord_flip()

2- coord_quickmap() sets the aspect ratio correctly for maps. This is very important if we’re plotting spatial data with “ggplot2”.

# install.packages("maps")
library(maps)
## Warning: package 'maps' was built under R version 3.6.2
##
## Attaching package: 'maps'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
##
##     map
us <- map_data("state")

ggplot(us, aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
geom_polygon(fill = "white", colour = "black")

ggplot(us, aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
 geom_polygon(fill = "white", colour = "black") +
 coord_quickmap()

3- coord_polar() uses polar coordinates. Polar coordinates reveal an interesting connection between a bar chart and a Coxcomb chart.

p2 <- p1 +
  geom_bar(
    mapping = aes(x = education, fill = education),
    show.legend = FALSE,
    width = 1
  ) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL)

p2 + coord_flip()

p2 + coord_polar()

The Layered Grammar of Graphics

In the previous sections, we learned a foundation that we can use to make any type of plot with “ggplot2”. To see this, let’s add position adjustments, stats, coordinate systems, and faceting to our code template:

ggplot(data = <DATA>) +
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(
     mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>),
     stat = <STAT>,
     position = <POSITION>
  ) +
  <COORDINATE_FUNCTION> +
  <FACET_FUNCTION>

Our new template takes seven parameters, the bracketed words that appear in the template. In practice, we rarely need to supply all seven parameters to make a graph because “ggplot2” will provide useful defaults for everything except the data, the mappings, and the geom function.

The seven parameters in the template compose the grammar of graphics, a formal system for building plots. The grammar of graphics is based on the insight that we can uniquely describe any plot as a combination of a dataset, a geom, a set of mappings, a stat, a position adjustment, a coordinate system, and a faceting scheme.
